Here is an example of how you can create a simple search bar using PHP:

**search.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database (replace with your own DB connection)
$conn = mysqli_connect("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

if (!$conn) {
    die("Connection failed: " . mysqli_connect_error());
}

// Get search query from form submission
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    $searchQuery = $_POST["search"];
    // Query database to get results
    $query = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$searchQuery%' LIMIT 10";
    $result = mysqli_query($conn, $query);
    if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
        while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
            echo "<p>" . $row["column_name"] . "</p>";
        }
    } else {
        echo "No results found.";
    }
}

?>

<!-- Search form -->
<form action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="post">
    <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<!-- Alternative: use AJAX for live search results -->
<script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.5.1/jquery.min.js"></script>
<script>
    $(document).ready(function() {
        $("#search-input").on("keyup", function() {
            var searchQuery = $(this).val();
            $.ajax({
                type: "POST",
                url: "<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>",
                data: { search: searchQuery },
                success: function(data) {
                    $("#results").html(data);
                }
            });
        });
    });
</script>

<!-- HTML structure for live search results -->
<div id="results"></div>
```
**Explanation**

This example assumes you have a MySQL database with a table named `table_name` and a column named `column_name`. The script connects to the database, gets the search query from the form submission, and queries the database to get matching results. If there are no results, it displays an error message.

The search bar uses a simple HTML form with an input field and a submit button. When the user submits the form, the PHP script processes the request and displays the search results.

Alternatively, you can use AJAX (with jQuery) to perform live search queries without reloading the page. This is achieved by adding JavaScript code that sends a POST request to the same PHP file whenever the user types something in the search input field. The PHP script then returns the search results as HTML, which are updated dynamically on the page.

Note: Make sure to replace the database connection parameters with your own values and update the table/column names according to your schema. Also, this is a basic example and you may want to add error handling, security measures (e.g., sanitizing user input), and improve performance for large datasets.

